max_threshold = 0.1
discrete_number = 0
continuous_number = 0

for (number_variable in colnames(mtcars)) {
  number_observation = mtcars[[number_variable]]
  
  if (is.numeric(number_observation)) {
    number = length(unique(number_observation)) / length(number_observation)
    if (number < max_threshold) {
      discrete_number = discrete_number + 1
    } else {
      continuous_number = continuous_number + 1
    }
  } else {
    discrete_number = discrete_number + 1
  }
}

Question 2

Use different visualization tools to summarize the data sets in this question.

  1. Using the PlantGrowth data set, visualize and compare the weight of the plant in the three separated group. Give labels to the title, x-axis, and y-axis on the graph. Write a paragraph to summarize your findings.
library(ggplot2)

# Load the data set
data("PlantGrowth")

# Head of the data set
head(PlantGrowth)
# Enter your code here!

library(ggplot2)

data("PlantGrowth")

data_graph = ggplot(PlantGrowth, aes(x = group, y = weight, fill = group)) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "bar", width = 0.5) +
  labs(
    title = "Average Plant Weight by Different Treatment Group",
    x = "Group",
    y = "Average Weight (grams)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

print(data_graph)

Result:

The chart above displays a comparison between the average weight of platns in three groups: Control, Treatment 1 and Treatment 2. It is evident that on average, plants recieiving treatment 1 exhibit lower weight in comparison to the control group. In contrast, plants in treatment 2 demonstrate an increase in average weight, suggesting that treatment two is more effective in increase weight of the plant or overall plant growth. As treatment one results in a decreased weight, it appears to be less effective an may not be the optimal treatment for plant growth.

  1. Using the USArrests data set, create a pairs plot to display the correlations between the variables in the data set. Plot the scatter plot with Murder and Assault. Give labels to the title, x-axis, and y-axis on the graph. Write a paragraph to summarize your results from both plots.
# Load the data set
data("USArrests")

# Head of the data set
head(USArrests)
# Enter your code here!

pairs(USArrests, main = "Pairs Plot of US Arrests")

plot(USArrests$Murder, USArrests$Assault,
     main = " Murder vs. Assault",
     xlab = "Murder Rate",
     ylab = "Assault Rate",
     col = "red")

Result: In the scatter plot, we observe a strong positive correlation between murder and assulat rates. This indicates that as the rate of assault increase, there is a corresponding increase in the rate of murders. This relationship suggestion that in areas with high assult rates, there is a high possibility that the murder rate are also high. The pairs plot provides critical information into the relationship between various variables such as rape, urban pop, murder, and assault. Murder and assault rates exhibit a positive correlation which reinforce findings from the scatter plot, however in contrast to urban popoulation, there are little correlation indication that murder rates is not a strong association with the size of the population. The variable of murder and rape shows a postie correlation suggesting that there is a similar trends between those types of violent crimes. Assault and rape have a positive correlation while assault and urban population have little relationship. But when looking at Urban population relationship with rape, there is a positive correlation, indicating that in area of high population, reported rape incidents are also high.

# Enter your code here!
library(ggplot2)

#bar graph to visualize the number of square foot over the years
bar_plot_average_sqft_by_year = ggplot(average_sqft_by_year, aes(x = Year_Built, y = Total_SqFt)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Average Square Footage by Year",
       x = "Year Built",
       y = "Average Square Footage") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 360, hjust = 0.5))

print(bar_plot_average_sqft_by_year)

# bar plot to visualize the number of houses built per year
house_count_by_year_graph = ggplot(house_count_by_year, aes(x = Year_Built, y = Num_Houses)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Number of Houses Built by Year",
       x = "Year Built",
       y = "Number of Houses") +
  theme_light() +

  1. Write a summary about your findings from this exercise.

The provided graph indicates that the year 2005 experienced a peak rate of housing construction and after theres a gradual decline from 2005 to 2010. Additionally there seems to be a decrease in construction rate after the year 2000 as observed by the increasing spacing between data points on the scatter plot. Looking at average square foot, most houses that were built had an average size of less than 200 square foot. Notably during the 1980s, houses had one of the largest average square foot before falling back down to under 200 sqft.
